Icon theme :: Baroque
=====================
ToDo:

You may notice that this so-called icon "theme" is nothing but a hodge-podge of images borrowed from other themes. This is correct, I have used elements of Tango, Oxygen, Gartoon and others to mock up a look'n'feel. It's a bit of a mess at the moment, but it serves for now. I am slowly replacing the majority with purpose-made graphics.

Dark Materials:
--------------
Polished wood, brass, ruby, amethyst and tanned leather. 

Specific Colours:
Amethyst: #550066 #883399 #aa66ee
Ruby: #990000 #cc0000 #dd6666
Mahogany: #663300 #996622 #bb9944
Tan: #994400 #cc8800 #ddbb66
Gold: #997700 #ffcc00 #ffdd66
Verdure: #446600 #668800 #99bb00
Cobalt: #003366 #446699 #88aacc
Steel: #332200 #554422 #776644 #998866 #bbaa88 #ddccaa 

Style pointers: 'steampunk' or the dashboard of a British 1960s sports car. Dark, mechanical and old-fashioned.

File formats: Master designs for desktop icons and in the file manager views should be 48x48 pixel SVGs. Bitmap icons should be RGBA PNG and the vector icons in SVG format. Toolbar icons should be 22x22 PNGs. Some 16x16 PNGs may be created for common list and menu icons.

Content: I intend to bring the icons more in line with http://tango.freedesktop.org/Icon_Metaphors, http://tango.freedesktop.org/Generic_Icon_Theme_Guidelines, http://standards.freedesktop.org/icon-naming-spec/icon-naming-spec-latest.html and http://standards.freedesktop.org/icon-theme-spec/icon-theme-spec-latest.html.

I suggest you use Free Software to produce the artwork. Try Inkscape for a vector editor and GIMP fits the bill perfectly as a bitmap icon editor. 

